  "prompt": "How do you determine the pH of hydrofluoric acid?",
  "response": "Determining the pH of hydrofluoric acid (HF) involves understanding its acidic properties and performing calculations based on its concentration and dissociation in water. Here's a step-by-step guide:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Understand the dissociation of HF in water**\n   Hydrofluoric acid is a weak acid, which means it does not completely dissociate in water. Its dissociation is represented by the following equilibrium:\n   \\[\n   HF \\rightleftharpoons H^+ + F^-\n   \\]\n   The dissociation constant (\\(K_a\\)) for HF is \\(7.2 \\times 10^{-4}\\).\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Write the expression for the acid dissociation constant (\\(K_a\\))**\n   \\[\n   K_a = \\frac{[H^+][F^-]}{[HF]}\n   \\]\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Set up the ICE table (Initial, Change, Equilibrium)**\n   Let the initial concentration of HF be \\([HF]_0\\). At equilibrium, some HF dissociates, producing \\([H^+]\\) and \\([F^-]\\).\n\n|          | HF      | \\(H^+\\) | \\(F^-\\) |\n|----------|---------|---------|---------|\n| Initial  | \\([HF]_0\\) | 0       | 0       |\n| Change   | \\(-x\\)  | \\(+x\\)  | \\(+x\\)  |\n| Equilibrium | \\([HF]_0 - x\\) | \\(x\\)   | \\(x\\)   |\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Substitute the equilibrium concentrations into the \\(K_a\\) expression**\n   \\[\n   K_a = \\frac{x \\cdot x}{[HF]_0 - x}\n   \\]\n   Assuming \\(x\\) is small compared to \\([HF]_0\\) (since HF is a weak acid), the equation simplifies to:\n   \\[\n   K_a \\approx \\frac{x^2}{[HF]_0}\n   \\]\n   Solve for \\(x\\):\n   \\[\n   x = \\sqrt{K_a \\cdot [HF]_0}\n   \\]\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Calculate the \\([H^+]\\) concentration**\n   \\[\n   [H^+] = x = \\sqrt{K_a \\cdot [HF]_0}\n   \\]\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Determine the pH**\n   The pH is calculated using the formula:\n   \\[\n   pH = -\\log[H^+]\n   \\]\n\n---\n\n### Example Calculation\nSuppose you have a 0.10 M solution of HF:\n\\[\nx = \\sqrt{7.2 \\times 10^{-4} \\times 0.10} = \\sqrt{7.2 \\times 10^{-5}} \\approx 8.49 \\times 10^{-3}\n\\]\n\\[\n[H^+] = 8.49 \\times 10^{-3} \\, \\text{M}\n\\]\n\\[\npH = -\\log(8.49 \\times 10^{-3}) \\approx 2.07\n\\]\n\n---\n\n### Notes:\n1. HF is a weak acid, so its pH is higher (less acidic) compared to strong acids like HCl of the same concentration.\n2. Safety precautions are essential when handling HF, as it is highly corrosive and toxic.",
